ning portrayals of nautical disasters in sixteenth- and seventeenth-century Spanish literature and culture. The essays collected here showcase shipwreck’s symbolic deployment to question colonial expansion and transoceanic trade; to critique the Christian enterprise overseas; to signal the collapse of dominant social order; and to relay moral messages and represent socio-political debates. The contributors find examples in poetry, theater, narrative fiction, and other print artifacts, and approach the topic variously through the lens of historical, literary, and cultural studies. Ultimately demonstrating how shipwrecks both shaped and destabilized perceptions of the Spanish Empire worldwide, this analytically rich volume is the first in Hispanic studies to investigate the darker side of mercantile and imperial expansion through maritime disaster.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aShipwrecks in literature. 0aSpanish literaturexSocial aspectsy16th century. 0aSpanish literaturexSocial aspectsy17th century. 0aSpanish literatureyClassical period, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  ashipwreck, Spanish empire, oceanic exploration, early modern Spain, transatlantic voyages, seafaring, trade, travel, nautical disaster, Spanish literature, Spanish culture, San Felipe.1 aBaena, Julio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaena, Julio.1 aBlackmore, Josiah.1 aHsu, Carmen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHsu, Carmen.1 aMansilla, Fernando Rodríguez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMansilla, Fernando Rodríguez.1 aMartín Santo, Noemí, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOhanna, Natalio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela